<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-498  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 498.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 4 1989 n1162 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical discs get ready to rub out the floppies.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fawcett, Neil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical disk technologies have responded to the growing need ofPCs for very-high-capacity storage and fast access in a compactsize.andP;  There are several optical disk technologies, includingCD-ROM, compact disk interactive (CD-I), write-once read-many(WORM), and erasable optical drives.andP;  CD-ROM is strictly apre-recorded storage technology, with products targeted atspecific user bases.andP;  CD-I is similar to CD-ROM but includesinteractive use of multiple forms of media stored on the disk.andO;WORM technology allows data to be written to the disk, but oncewritten, data can not be erased.andP;  Erasable optical disks, thelatest optical technology, use such technologies as Verbatim'sthermo-magneto-optical process to store and erase data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CD-ROMWORMIndustry AnalysisErasable Optical MemorySystem DevelopmentTrendsSystem Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>